  "opinion": "In my eighty-six years, I've seen science evolve from the quiet, hands-on work of a few to the vast, interconnected field it is today. The gender gap in science is not a simple question of numbers but a story of opportunity and barriers that have been there for decades. When I was young, my parents—both educated in their time—taught me that curiosity was the greatest teacher, but they also showed me that society often steered girls toward domestic roles while boys were encouraged to explore the sciences. Today, I’ve watched as more women enter STEM fields, yet the gap persists in leadership roles and high-impact research. This gap is not just about who gets to study science but who gets to lead it, shape its future, and benefit from its discoveries. It’s a gap that needs addressing, but not with quick fixes or one-size-fits-all solutions. We must create environments where women feel safe to ask questions, make mistakes, and contribute without fear of judgment. For example, mentorship programs that pair young women with female scientists who have navigated similar paths can build confidence and provide practical guidance. Also, schools should start early by encouraging girls to see science as a creative and collaborative endeavor, not just a male-dominated arena. The key is to foster a culture where everyone feels valued, not just those who fit the traditional mold. As a retired woman who has spent her life learning and teaching through hobbies like hiking and cycling, I believe that the most powerful changes come from patience and understanding, not pressure. We must address the gap with the same care and respect we show for the natural world we study.",
